The monsoon arrived in August that year without warning, the way it always does in Odisha — as if it had been gathering patience for months and had finally decided to stop.

By ten o'clock in the morning, the college compound was two inches under water in the low places, and the drain near the main gate had surrendered its function entirely. Students moved in clusters under umbrellas, holding their bags above their heads, navigating the path from the hostel block to the lecture halls with the specific concentration of people crossing a river that wasn't supposed to be there.

Vicky's shoes gave out at the main gate.

They were canvas shoes, bought from a roadside stall near Bhubaneswar station for sixty-eight rupees. They had lasted almost four months, which was better than anyone who had seen them would have predicted. But the monsoon had been waiting specifically for them, and on that particular Tuesday morning, the left sole separated from the upper near the toe, making a wet, flat sound against the ground with every step.

He walked on anyway, his left sock soaking immediately, his face giving no indication that anything had changed.

Prince Rathore was standing under the large awning near the reception block with three of his friends. Prince was in his second year, but his position in the college hierarchy had nothing to do with years and everything to do with his father, who was an MLA from a district that seemed to produce exactly two things: good mangoes and local politicians. Prince had arrived on the first day of the semester in a white Ambassador with a driver, a fact that the entire hostel had discussed for two days.

He noticed Vicky's shoe at the gate.

"Hey," Prince said, loudly enough to carry through the rain noise. His group turned. Other students, passing, slowed. "Your shoe is speaking. Somebody forgot to teach it how to shut up."

His friends laughed. The sound of it was a particular kind of college-corridor laughter — the kind that isn't really laughter, just a signal to whoever is watching that the speaker has allies.

Vicky looked at his shoe. Then he looked at Prince. Then he walked on.

He didn't say anything. He walked through the gate with the left sole flopping on every step, his bag over his head as a makeshift umbrella, and disappeared into the crowd near the physics block.

Prince watched him go, still grinning.

---

At three that afternoon, a white Ambassador with a PCR number plate turned into the college compound and parked near the hostel block. This was unusual. PCR vehicles did not normally make visits to medical college hostels at three in the afternoon.

The SHO of the local police station, a large man named Inspector Mathur, climbed out. He was in uniform, his shirt buttoned correctly, carrying a white cardboard box under one arm. He consulted a piece of paper in his other hand, then walked toward the hostel reception.

Adarsh, who was in the corridor near the stairs when this happened, watched the entire thing from the first floor railing.

The SHO found Vicky on the ground floor near the water filter.

"Vikram Ahuja?" he said.

"Yes," Vicky said.

The SHO set the cardboard box on the concrete ledge of the water filter area. "From Inspector Ahuja, Bhubaneswar city police station. Your uncle sends his regards." He paused, his expression that of a man who has delivered many things over the course of his career and finds them all equally routine. "He heard your shoes were giving you trouble."

Vicky opened the box. Inside was a pair of tan leather shoes, polished, the laces already threaded and tied loosely. His size. Correct size.

He looked at them for a moment.

"Thank you," he said.

The SHO nodded, turned around, walked back to the white Ambassador, and left. The entire visit had taken perhaps six minutes.

---

The news moved through the hostel the way news moves in enclosed places — before dinner, everyone in the building knew. By the time Adarsh reached the canteen that evening, three people had already asked him if it was true. He said yes. They said nothing in response, which is what people say when they are recalibrating something.

Prince Rathore was at a table near the far wall, eating quietly, his eyes down.

He did not look up when Vicky walked in. He remained very interested in his plate of rice.

After that, whenever Vicky was in a corridor or a classroom, Prince seemed to find reasons to be somewhere else in that corridor or classroom. The comments that Prince had previously made freely in front of crowds — about clothes, about money, about which family owned what — dried up entirely in Vicky's vicinity. Not dramatically. Not with any visible effort. They simply stopped.

Adarsh mentioned none of this to Vicky. He wasn't sure Vicky had noticed. He suspected, later, that Vicky had noticed everything and had simply decided it wasn't worth discussing.

---

That night, Vicky wore the new leather shoes to the canteen for dinner. He had taken the damaged canvas ones and put them in a bag near the bin, though he hadn't thrown them out yet.

He ate his rice. He didn't mention the SHO, or the box, or his uncle, or Prince Rathore.

After dinner, walking back to the hostel room across the wet stone courtyard, the new leather shoes made a firm, dry sound on the ground. A good sound. The kind a shoe is supposed to make.

Adarsh, walking beside him, said: "Those fit well."

"Yes," Vicky said.

"He knew your size."

"My uncle has always been particular about shoes," Vicky said. "He says you can tell everything about a man from whether his feet are comfortable."

Adarsh thought about this. "What does it tell you if your shoe falls apart at the gate?"

Vicky considered the question with complete seriousness. "That you have been walking too far for too long in the wrong shoes," he said, "and that it was time for better ones."

He walked on. The leather shoes made their firm, dry sound on the stone.

Adarsh looked down at his own shoes, which were also canvas and had also been showing stress near the left toe. He decided not to mention this at all.

